knowledgebase.title: Frontend: Bug Management Module
knowledgebase.description:
Flow and Process
  • Create folder like Project
  • Under the project it creates default backend and frontend section
  • If you're a frontend can show only frontend else otherwise
  • If QA only see the for checking updates
  • Create a Bug specification (title, description, status = pending, for checking, completed)
  • Upon changing to start, get the date and set the target date
  • If started do a timer on the header else none
  • Set a priority like P1, P2, P3, P4
UI/UX
  • Similar to cards but on dropdown accordion type so easier to see but they are on a container jumbotron like
  • Dev view: listed all the pending on the upper first section
  • Dev view: listed all the for checking on the 2nd section
  • Dev view: listed all the completed status on 3rd section
  • They all are paginated
  • For decision they could be either horizontally or vertically

knowledgebase.title: Frontend & Backend: Payment Integration
knowledgebase.description:
Full Backend + Frontend Integration (Recommended)

How it works:

Frontend requests your backend to create an order.

Backend calls PayPal API to create an order and gets an order ID.

Frontend renders PayPal button using that order ID.

On approval, PayPal returns info to frontend, which then calls your backend to capture/confirm payment via PayPal API.

Backend verifies payment and updates your database.

Pros: More secure. You dont trust the frontend for payment confirmation.

Flow Diagram:
Frontend -> Backend -> PayPal create order
Frontend -> PayPal checkout using order ID
PayPal -> Frontend (onApprove)
Frontend -> Backend to capture & verify
Backend -> Database update
